04466nmm a2200673Ia 9781501704017DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979905765  a97815017040177 a10.7591/97815017040172doi  a(DE-B1597)478506  a(OCoLC)948756554  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a327.1142231 aMontgomery, Evan Braden, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Hegemon's Shadow :bLeading States and the Rise of Regional Powers /cEvan Braden Montgomery. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b2 maps, 2 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between established powers and emerging powers is one of the most important topics in world politics. Nevertheless, few studies have investigated how the leading state in the international system responds to rising powers in peripheral regions—actors that are not yet and might never become great powers but that are still increasing their strength, extending their influence, and trying to reorder their corner of the world. In the Hegemon’s Shadow fills this gap. Evan Braden Montgomery draws on different strands of realist theory to develop a novel framework that explains why leading states have accommodated some rising regional powers but opposed others. Montgomery examines the interaction between two factors: the type of local order that a leading state prefers and the type of local power shift that appears to be taking place. The first captures a leading state’s main interest in a peripheral region and serves as the baseline for its evaluation of any changes in the status quo. Would the leading state like to see a balance of power rather than a preponderance of power, does it favor primacy over parity instead, or is it impartial between these alternatives? The second indicates how a local power shift is likely to unfold. In particular, which regional order is an emerging power trying to create and does a leading state expect it to succeed? Montgomery tests his arguments by analyzing Great Britain’s efforts to manage the rise of Egypt, the Confederacy, and Japan during the nineteenth century and the United States’ efforts to manage the emergence of India and Iraq during the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGreat powersxForeign relations. 0aGreat powersxHistoryx19th century. 0aGreat powersxHistoryx20th century. 0aGreat powersxHistoryy19th century. 0aGreat powersxHistoryy20th century. 0aHegemony. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aleading state, international system, rising powers, power shift, balance of power.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170401740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501704017423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501704017/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016